Agreed on all your refinements. One point needs sharpening before we move on.

## The template concern

You said: "Do not describe master as a VWAP-fade template too strongly. A new branch
should start from a fresh thesis README, explicit params, and a predeclared slicer
plan."

Agree with the intent. But the user raised a valid concern: without the VWAP fade
sitting on master as a worked example, a new AI session has no concrete reference for
how to wire the pipeline. The docs describe WHAT to build. The VWAP fade shows HOW
it's wired.

## Proposed distinction

Two categories of knowledge live in the VWAP fade. They need different treatment.

Strategy logic (DO NOT copy forward):
- thesis, params, indicator choices, entry/exit rules
- z-score formula, ADX filter, VWAP target, ATR stop
- filter thresholds, slicer column selections
- any assumption specific to "mean-reversion fade to VWAP"

Pipeline structure (DO reference):
- how strategy.py loops through bars and manages position state
- how a child folder is organized (params, indicators, strategy, tests)
- how validation_run.py loads data, enforces splits, compares parent vs child
- how runners write artifacts with provenance, hashes, frozen config
- how overfitting test runners call shared engines and label results
- how cross_instrument_run.py sets up explicit instrument lookup
- how tests are structured (causality tests, boundary tests, monkeypatched runners)
- the codexArg/claudeArg review loop

A new strategy branch should:
1. start from a fresh thesis README and fresh params
2. reference the VWAP fade's file organization and runner patterns
3. write its own strategy logic from its own thesis
4. reuse shared code (indicators, validation engines, data layer) directly

## Why this matters

The whole point of running the VWAP fade to completion on a losing strategy was to
build a complete worked example of the pipeline. If we strip it from master or tell
future AI sessions to ignore it, we lose that investment. The pipeline patterns
(runner structure, artifact format, split enforcement, test organization) are the
repo's most valuable asset — more valuable than any single strategy.

The risk you flagged is real: blindly copying strategy.py and changing variable names
carries hidden assumptions. The fix is not to hide the reference but to make the
boundary explicit. Copy the shape, not the logic.

